<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-343-729  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 343 729.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Personal Computing  March 1989 v13 n3 p103(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>What's new in scanning. (includes related article on opticalcharacter recognition) (computer scanners)</TITLE><AUTHOR>O'Malley, Christopher.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Gray scale scanners, much better at reproducing photographs andother complex images than other graphics scanners, aretransforming the scanner from an attractive extra to a practicalperipheral.andP;  Gray scale technology is the broad term being used inthe computer industry to describe an emerging class ofsophisticated scanners, software and accessories.andP;  This technologyis advancing on three fronts: better and cheaper gray-scalescanners, new image-editing software, and laser printerenhancements that make gray-scale printing at the desktop level apossibility.andP;  Although dealing with gray-scale is somewhatcomplex, users benefit from the potential for much sharperhalftones, increased control over the appearance of the image, andthe ability to take advantage of laser typesetters.andP;  Drawbacksinclude massive files sizes and lengthy printing times.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ScanningTechnologyAnalysisOptical Character Readers.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Scanning information - manufacturers' information. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>